VL  - 2024
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105027845116&partnerID=40&md5=4681dec39ca3b2378720d3e3f23c3b7b
AB  - Earthquake catastrophe risk modelling is essential in mitigating the earthquake risk via comprehensive risk quantification for seismic design, resilience enhancement, catastrophe insurance programs and efficient post event response efforts. Traditional approaches of earthquake catastrophe risk modelling inherit a large degree of uncertainty that poses great challenges in their application. Machine Learning (ML) has been proved to be a powerful tool for various tasks in earthquake engineering, resulting in risk quantification accuracy improvement and uncertainty reduction in the modelling results. In this paper, we review the challenges in traditional risk modelling approaches and the latest developments in ML-based methods for various components applicable to earthquake risk modelling which can address the challenges. Different ML algorithms, such as XGBoost, Random Forest, and Neural Networks, are used in components including ground motion prediction, site amplification, damage and loss estimate. Bayesian optimization is used to find the optimum parameters for each model and SHAP analysis is used to study the sensitivity of the selected hyperparameters. The earthquake catastrophe risk modelling framework is enhanced by integrating the ML models for various components, the stochastic earthquake occurrence simulation and the financial loss calculation. The Japanese earthquake ground motion records, site conditions, and detailed damage data from the March 11, 2011 Great East Japan Earthquake are used to construct and calibrate the proposed ML based components. Using the Zenkyoren exposure in Japan as an example, a number of recent earthquakes in Japan are used to further verify the accuracy of the proposed model. The verification demonstrates that the proposed model has higher accuracy and less uncertainty and can serve as a better alternative to the traditional models in Japan. © 2024, International Association for Earthquake Engineering. All rights reserved.
