AB  - The Himalayan region, formed by the collision of the stable Eurasian plate with the northward-moving Indian plate, is one of the most tectonically active areas in the world. This complex tectonic environment leads to significant seismic hazards, yet the scarcity of recorded ground motion data in the region poses challenges for developing reliable ground motion models (GMMs) and accurately assessing seismic risks. To address these limitations, a stochastic finite-fault ground motion simulation approach is employed, leveraging locally calibrated input parameters for India's central and western Himalayan shallow crustal regions. A large ensemble of synthetic ground motions is generated using these parameters. Based on the simulated data, a nonparametric GMM for horizontal spectral acceleration is developed for the region using artificial neural networks. The model is specifically developed for a reference site with an average shear wave velocity of 760 m/s, ensuring adaptability to site-specific conditions beyond the study region. Mixed-effect regression is carried out to quantify the total standard deviation of spectral ordinates. The model's applicability for the study region is demonstrated by incorporating local soil amplification effects for various site classes and evaluating against recorded ground motions and local and global GMMs. The proposed model aligns well with observed ground motions, offering an improved model for seismic hazard assessment in the region. This model effectively mitigates the limitations caused by the scarcity of recorded ground motion data while providing a robust tool for understanding seismic hazards in the central and western Himalayas. © 2025 American Society of Civil Engineers.
