UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85127254995&doi=10.1007%2Fs00024-022-02997-y&partnerID=40&md5=dc8650ba0a539274750a7a3f73068b3a
AB  - Local site conditions, especially complex topography and geological structure, play a critical role in determining the peak acceleration and spectral representation of ground motions under earthquakes; however, they are not yet considered sufficiently in ground motion prediction equations. The scattering of seismic waves by complex site conditions leads to complexity for quantifying the relation among incident waves, site conditions, and site amplification effect based on traditional regression technology. This article explores the prediction performance for local site amplification effect on ground motion using a machine learning-based model, including the support vector machine, extreme learning machine, classical artificial neural network, and two optimizing algorithms with an artificial neural network. A typical local topography, a canyon with cliffs, is studied as an example, and the site amplification effect generated by scattering is determined by the boundary element method. The results indicate that the extreme learning machine and artificial neural network can predict the local site effect of ground motion, while the support vector machine does not yield reliable estimates. The particle swarm optimization and adaptive differential evolution can improve the predicted accuracy, and the adaptive differential evolution-artificial neural network algorithm has slightly better performance and stability. The incident frequency and depth of cliffs are significant parameters for the site amplification effect, whereas the depth of the V-shaped canyon is relatively insignificant. © 2022, The Author(s), under exclusive licence to Springer Nature Switzerland AG.
